snippet.textDisplay:
Was served a 16 min overclockers UK advert before this. Let it play so you get the ad revenue.

It was full of errors.
The dude thought N link was the first WiFi standard and it operates only at 2.4Ghz.
Advertised the AX WiFi standard for streamers (opposed to a cable which is cheaper and more stable.), Whilst also saying it improves the range because it provides 6000 Mbps so it goes further.
Then suggested that all devices would save battery connecting to this router because of WiFi6. "All devices."
Advertised the WiFi as more secure as it supports WPA3... Failed to mention most devices cannot use that standard yet.

Totally avoided mentioning cost.
Waffled for 10 of the 16 minutes.

Advertised this as a way of reducing ping and lag.... Failed to mention internet connection.

So glad I had tech news to clean my brain afterwards.

snippet.textDisplay:
Hey... Uh... Linus... About that whole Force thing... You do realize that Luke never used the Force to so much as move an object until Episode V right? Like. People who watched Empire when it came out, and watched Luke pull his saber from the snow, were like "whoa wtf the wizards can move stuff with their minds now???" 

So let's keep that in mind. Along with the many other new additions to the Star Wars canon, there are no rules broken, because there's no set rulebook for The Force. 

Is it reasonable that a Jedi could heal with The Force? Of course. Did The Rise of Skywalker play it out too much, especially since it first appeared in the new canon not two days before in The Mandalorian, and possibly even use it as a crutch? Yes. 

Is it reasonable that two Force users could communicate through the Force? See each other? Their locations? Of course. What else are the Force Ghosts doing? When Obi-Wan tells Luke to use the Force to blow up the Death Star, do you think Kenobi couldn't see it go down? Or do you think he was just doing a random checkup on Luke? Now, is it reasonable they could transfer objects through space? Honestly, yes. Hyperspace is mid-dimensional travel, so why couldn't a space wizard just conjure it up?

I love you Linus. But step back and look at the big picture here. We've had 43 years of surprises and "rule-breaking" additions to the canon since A New Hope came out. TROS may have jumped the gun and added more than usual and relied on it more than usual, but I think we''ll be okay. 

Go read a good Star Wars novel and you'll see what I mean. It's not canon anymore, But I would recommend Star Wars: Shatterpoint by Matthew Stover. It's an excellent read and will keep you on the edge of your loungechair.

This 2FA hack was kinda their fault. They (from what I've read) just have a software which generates the RSA tokens on their PCs. The catch is that this program should only work on this PC, when copied to another it should block itself. But as these geniuses use Windows, where the hackers simply got administrative rights, they could copy some IDs from the one PC to their own, which resulted in the software thinking its still on the right PC and returning a RSA token.

Well, you could simply try not being that dumb, stop having 2FA generators on the PC where you use the codes. That's not the point lmao
